Title
Ingest & Store Real-Time Telemetry from Power Converters via IoT Protocols

Tutorial Breakdown (60 Minutes)
0–5 min: Introduction & Motivation

Why this matters: High-frequency telemetry for predictive maintenance and grid optimization.
Challenges: EMI environments, kilohertz sampling, secure transport, scalable storage.
Goal: Build an open-source pipeline (MQTT → Kafka → TimescaleDB) with sub-200 ms latency.


5–15 min: Edge Telemetry Collection (MQTT)

Concepts:

MQTT basics: lightweight pub/sub for IoT.
QoS levels and TLS 1.3 for secure transport.


Implementation:

Converter-embedded MQTT clients.
Local buffering and backfill strategies.


Demo:

Show MQTT client publishing voltage/current data at 10 kHz.
Use EMQX broker with X.509 certificates.




15–25 min: Transport & Buffering (Apache Kafka)

Why Kafka?

Fault-tolerant buffering, horizontal scalability.


Setup:

Kafka cluster (3 nodes).
Kafka Connect bridge from MQTT.


Demo:

Visualize message flow from MQTT → Kafka topics.
Show partitioning for high throughput (12.9 MB/s ingest).




25–35 min: Stream Processing (ksqlDB)

Real-time analytics:

Windowed aggregations for THD and dv/dt.
Anomaly scoring for predictive maintenance.


Demo:

Run ksqlDB queries on Kafka topics.
Show real-time THD calculation and alert generation.




35–45 min: Time-Series Storage (TimescaleDB)

Why TimescaleDB?

Hypertables for high-velocity data.
Continuous aggregates for fast queries.


Policies:

Retention and compression for cost control.


Demo:

Insert telemetry into TimescaleDB.
Query historical trends efficiently.




45–55 min: Visualization & ML Integration

Dashboards:

Grafana/Tableau for live monitoring.


ML pipeline:

Python API for batch export and retraining.


Demo:

Show Grafana dashboard with real-time THD and anomaly alerts.
Briefly outline ML retraining workflow.




55–60 min: Wrap-Up & Q&A

Key takeaways:

Open-source stack for real-time telemetry.
Predictive maintenance benefits (25 min earlier fault alerts).


Resources:

GitHub repo with sample configs.
References for deeper reading.




✅ Suggested Materials

Slides: Architecture diagrams, code snippets.
Live Demo: MQTT → Kafka → TimescaleDB → Grafana.
Sample Configs: Docker Compose for quick setup.


